the minnesota supreme court has upheld 
the murder conviction and sentence of david brom who was found 
guilty in the ax slayings of four members of his family 
brom was convicted of four counts of firstdegree murder in the 
february 1988 deaths in rochester of his parents bernard and 
paulette his sister diane and his younger brother ricky 
a public defender susan maki had appealed to the supreme 
court arguing broms rights were violated when a change of venue 
request was denied and when psychiatric testimony was barred from 
the trials first phase 
maki said evidence showed that brom who had pleaded innocent by 
reason of mental illness was indeed mentally ill 
brom was sentenced in october 1989 to three life sentences and 
maki also had argued olmsted county district judge ancy morse 
abused the courts discretion in imposing the sentence 
the court rejected makis arguments in its decision disclosed 
friday by the olmsted county attorneys office which received an 
early copy of the ruling 
