the nations roman catholic bishops said 
saturday they are worried by indications of growing antisemitism 
especially during the current presidential campaign 
they said they plan to condemn hatred toward jews and voice 
regret for antisemitic acts committed onppolish soil in a 
longawaited pastoral letter early next year 
the text of the letter to be read at masses on jan 20 was not 
disclosed saturday but the episcopate said it responds to signs 
of antisemitism which are growing stronger especially during 
the presidential campaign 
the document which will deal with the centuriesold tradition 
of antisemitism in poland was drafted after two years work by 
the episcopate commission for dialogue with judaism 
it was long awaited by international jewish groups and expected 
to have enormous influence in poland where 93 percent of the 38 
million people consider themselves catholics 
the commission felt obliged to repeat the words of the holy 
father polishborn pope john paul ii who said during ceremonies 
to mark the 50th anniversary of world war ii that hostility and 
hatred toward judaism is in contradiction to christian values of 
human dignity the epsicopate said in a statement to the official 
pap news agency 
the rev stanislaw musial the commission secretary recently 
said poles should ask forgiveness for doing too little to save jews 
during world war ii and wipe out antisemitism 
his statement was the first by a ranking church official to 
address polishcatholic culpability in the nazi extermination of 3 
million polish jews during world war ii and discrimination suffered 
by jews in poland before and after the war only a few thousand 
jews remain in poland 
the american jewish congress published an open letter in 
midnovember expressing distress that the bishops had not yet 
issued their letter and that the current resurgence of 
antisemitism in poland has not been sufficently addressed by the 
church 
antisemitism has tainted polands first democratic presidential 
election and hate grafitti can be seen throughout the country 
rumors circulated that the devoutly catholic prime minister 
tadeusz mazowiecki was jewish or that his government was dominated 
by jews and questioners consistently raised the issue at campaign 
events mazowiecki was defeated in the elections first round a 
week ago but analysts attributed the loss mainly to discontent 
with economic reforms 
